      "writtenOn": "2017-05-17T18:35:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thanks for the derivation and the detailed explanation. However, I am not sure I follow you. What you describe seems to be exactly MulDiv255Round. At the same time, you say at the beginning of your comment \"I don\u0027t think any of SkPMSrcOver, SkMulDiv255Round, or the previous code are really correct.\"\n\nWhen I put SkMulDiv255Round in your driver it just works fine and gives a nice \"ok\". I both used my definition \n\n  result_i \u003d src_i + rint(g(src_alpha, dst_i))\n\nwith g(x, y) \u003d ((255 - x) * y) / 255 (which is the one given in the comment I wrote below) and the one used in Skia:\n\nhttps://cs.chromium.org/chromium/src/third_party/skia/include/core/SkMath.h?l\u003d115\u0026rcl\u003da281dd37e2b409db22f982ec9fee883e99e07daa\n\nWhich also seems to be algebraically equivalent to the one you propose above. Maybe the confusion arises from how I wrote the formula in my comment (which is more how a mathematician would write it, rather than a programmer)? As a C programmer I would write the same like this:\n\n  uint8_t srcover_muldiv255round(uint8_t src, uint8_t src_alpha, uint8_t dst) {\n    double g \u003d ((255.0 - (double)src_alpha) * (double)dst) / 255.0;\n    return src + (int)rint(g);\n  }\n\nThis is fundamentally what we are trying to achieve... the Skia version only uses some tricks to avoid doubles and make the thing faster.\n\nAnyway, if it is MulDiv255Round you are after, then I already wrote a version of it using NEON. As I said in the commit message, it is slower than the one I propose here. But if it is correctness you are after, then I guess this is the right way to go. I can re-run the benchmarks on it, if you confirm there is no misunderstanding.",
      "parentUuid": "a43b3c8e_94d8fc4c",
      "revId": "cb2f18af0ac87c34e010a0d3b695ed5911735893",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
